                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d979">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/16001: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-29T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 29, 1940—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>233. Chungking’s 300, June 26, 8 p.m., and 302, June 27, 4 p.m., bombing of
                    Chungking and 303, June 28, 7 p.m.<note n="85" xml:id="d979fn85">None
                        printed.</note> The Department authorizes you, in your discretion and as
                    occasion and appropriate opportunity therefor occur, to continue to bring to the
                    attention of appropriate officers of the Japanese Foreign Office this
                    Government’s attitude as repeatedly expressed, both upon broad humanitarian
                    grounds and upon the ground of danger to American life and property, toward
                    bombings of civilian populations such as those reported in the telegrams under
                    reference.</p>
                <p>Sent to Tokyo via Peiping. Repeated to Chungking and Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
